        <section class="section-border">
            <h2>Internal Links</h2>
            <p>Generally, the preferable way of including internal links in HTML pages is using <em>relative links</em>.</p>
            <p><strong>Absolute links</strong> specify the complete URL of the linked page, including the protocol (http/https), domain, and path. They are useful when linking to external resources or when the structure of the website might change.</p>
            <p><strong>Relative links</strong> specify the path to the linked page relative to the current page's location. They are advantageous within the same website structure, as they simplify maintenance and allow for easier restructuring of directories.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="section-border">
            <h2>Image Formats in Web Development</h2>
            <p>Common image formats used in web development are <mark>JPG</mark>, <mark>GIF</mark>, <mark>PNG</mark>, <mark>WEBP</mark>, and <mark>SVG</mark>.</p>
            <p><strong>JPG (Joint Photographic Experts Group)</strong> is suitable for photographs and complex images, offering good compression but losing quality with each save due to its lossy compression.</p>
            <p><strong>GIF (Graphics Interchange Format)</strong> supports animations and transparency but has a limited color palette and is not suitable for complex images due to its lossless compression.</p>
            <p><strong>PNG (Portable Network Graphics)</strong> supports transparency and is lossless, making it ideal for images with text or graphics and for images that require transparent backgrounds.</p>
            <p><strong>WEBP</strong> is a modern image format developed by Google, offering both lossy and lossless compression, smaller file sizes compared to JPG and PNG, and support for animation and transparency.</p>
            <p><strong>SVG (Scalable Vector Graphics)</strong> is an XML-based vector image format, ideal for logos, icons, and graphics that need to scale without losing quality.</p>
        </section>

